4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA REQUESTING AN INTERIM STUDY ON COORDINATING EFFORTS BETWEEN THE
6 DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES AND THE OFFICE OF PUBLIC
7 INSTRUCTION TO ADDRESS THE IMPACTS OF PRENATAL EXPOSURE TO METHAMPHETAMINE AND
8 FENTANYL ON CHILDREN; AND REQUIRING THAT THE FINAL RESULTS OF THE STUDY BE REPORTED
9 TO THE 70TH LEGISLATURE.
10
11 WHEREAS, an increasing number of babies born in Montana have been exposed to methamphetamine
12 and fentanyl in utero; and
13 WHEREAS, the long-term impacts of prenatal exposure to methamphetamine and fentanyl include an
14 increased risk of developmental delays, cognitive impairments, and learning disabilities; and
15 WHEREAS, this increased risk can be further exacerbated in areas of concentrated poverty that are
16 affected by generational trauma;
17 WHEREAS, the State-Tribal Relations Committee is the statutory committee charged with encouraging
18 state-tribal cooperation and local government-tribal cooperation and with conducting interim studies as
19 assigned;
20 WHEREAS, a coordinated effort between the department of public health and human services and the
21 office of public instruction to address these long-term impacts holds the most promise in addressing the health
22 and learning needs of children who had prenatal exposure to methamphetamine and fentanyl.
23
24 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
25 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
26 That the Legislative Council be requested to designate an appropriate interim committee or statutory
27 committee, pursuant to section 5-5-217, MCA, to examine how the department of public health and human
28 services and the office of public instruction can best coordinate their efforts to address the health and learning
